The bug is clear. The `UCL_STATE_INIT` block has a comment "Skip any spaces" at line 1664 but contains **no actual whitespace-skipping code**. `ucl_skip_comments` (line 1658) only skips `#` and `/* */` comments — it does not skip whitespace. When the input file `11.in` starts with two newlines and three spaces before `{`, `chunk->pos` still points to `\n` after `ucl_skip_comments` returns. The subsequent check `if (*p == '[')` and `if (*p == '{')` both fail since `*p == '\n'`, so the state goes to `UCL_STATE_KEY` without consuming `{`. Later, in `UCL_STATE_KEY`, whitespace is properly skipped and the parser reaches `{`, but `ucl_parse_key` has no handler for `{` as the first character of a key, producing the "key must begin with a letter" error.

---

**ROOT CAUSE:** `src/ucl_parser.c:1664` — In the `UCL_STATE_INIT` branch, the code has a comment "Skip any spaces" but performs no actual whitespace skipping before inspecting `*p` to detect an opening `[` or `{`. `ucl_skip_comments()` only skips comment syntax (`#…` and `/*…*/`), not whitespace. When the input has any leading whitespace (newlines, spaces) before the `{`, `*p` is not `{`, so the opening brace is never consumed; the parser enters `UCL_STATE_KEY` and then `ucl_parse_key` encounters `{` as the first character of what it expects to be a key identifier, causing the error "key must begin with a letter".

**LOCAL FIX:** Add a whitespace-skipping loop immediately after `p = chunk->pos;` inside the `UCL_STATE_INIT` else-block, before the `[`/`{` check:

```c
else {
    /* Skip any spaces */
    p = chunk->pos;
    while (p < chunk->end && ucl_test_character (*p, UCL_CHARACTER_WHITESPACE_UNSAFE)) {
        ucl_chunk_skipc (chunk, p);
    }
    if (*p == '[') {
        parser->state = UCL_STATE_VALUE;
        ucl_chunk_skipc (chunk, p);
    }
    else {
        parser->state = UCL_STATE_KEY;
        if (*p == '{') {
            ucl_chunk_skipc (chunk, p);
        }
    }
}
```

**GLOBAL FIX:** Extract a shared `ucl_skip_whitespace_and_comments(parser)` helper that skips both whitespace and comment sequences, and call it consistently at every state-machine entry point that currently calls `ucl_skip_comments`. This eliminates the recurring pattern of `ucl_skip_comments` followed by an implicit assumption that the cursor is on a non-whitespace character — a pattern that already exists correctly in `UCL_STATE_KEY` (lines 1679–1681) and `UCL_STATE_AFTER_VALUE` but was simply omitted in `UCL_STATE_INIT`.
